48
00:03:17.837 --> 00:03:19.454
Lawsuits.

49
00:03:19.614 --> 00:03:21.931
Threats.
Recriminations.

50
00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:25.353
This is a situation
no firm ever wants to be in.

51
00:03:25.479 --> 00:03:27.847
It's... Well. it's embarrassing.

52
00:03:28.376 --> 00:03:29.587
[Sighs]

53
00:03:29.643 --> 00:03:32.798
I know we all want
a swift resolution here.

54
00:03:33.212 --> 00:03:35.298
So what are our options?

55
00:03:35.394 --> 00:03:37.324
Take it to trial.

56
00:03:37.372 --> 00:03:38.673
Expensive.

57
00:03:38.728 --> 00:03:42.290
And extremely damaging
for HHM's reputation.

58
00:03:42.370 --> 00:03:46.329
Not my first choice or yours.
I imagine.

59
00:03:47.189 --> 00:03:49.540
The firm could choose
to buy me out

60
00:03:49.767 --> 00:03:53.728
for an amount that is
almost certain to bankrupt it.

61
00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:57.200
I spent decades
building this firm.

62
00:03:57.595 --> 00:04:00.447
I Don't want to be the agent
of its destruction.

63
00:04:02.389 --> 00:04:04.517
There is a third option.

64
00:04:04.815 --> 00:04:05.994
There's no reason

65
00:04:06.042 --> 00:04:09.573
we can't put all this
unpleasantness behind us

66
00:04:09.797 --> 00:04:12.783
and continue on as we have been.

67
00:04:13.111 --> 00:04:16.064
I'm willing
to let bygones be bygones.

68
00:04:16.400 --> 00:04:18.725
And if you agree.

69
00:04:18.970 --> 00:04:21.525
I think we can settle all this
right now

70
00:04:21.676 --> 00:04:23.676
with a simple handshake.

71
00:04:26.446 --> 00:04:28.876
Would you all give us the room
for a moment?

72
00:04:38.616 --> 00:04:39.884
[Door opens]

73
00:04:40.041 --> 00:04:42.441
[Indistinct conversations]

74
00:04:48.947 --> 00:04:50.892
17 years.

75
00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:54.275
18 in July. actually.

76
00:04:54.844 --> 00:04:58.751
All those years
we built this place together.

77
00:04:59.055 --> 00:05:02.595
And all that time
I've supported you.

78
00:05:03.117 --> 00:05:05.017
Looked up to you.

79
00:05:05.736 --> 00:05:07.603
deferred to you.

80
00:05:08.114 --> 00:05:09.673
Because I always thought

81
00:05:09.853 --> 00:05:12.119
you had the best interests
of the firm in mind.

82
00:05:12.215 --> 00:05:13.220
I have...

83
00:05:13.286 --> 00:05:16.314
Mnh.
You did.

84
00:05:16.831 --> 00:05:18.462
For a long time.

85
00:05:19.025 --> 00:05:20.626
But you've let
personal vendettas

86
00:05:20.729 --> 00:05:23.599
turn your focus away
from what's best for HHM.

87
00:05:23.733 --> 00:05:25.525
You've put your needs first.

88
00:05:25.696 --> 00:05:27.767
To our detriment.
I Don't think that's accurate.

89
00:05:27.937 --> 00:05:29.967
And the moment
that I mildly suggest.

90
00:05:30.044 --> 00:05:31.454
with empathy and concern.

91
00:05:31.535 --> 00:05:35.056
that maybe it's time for you
to consider retirement...

92
00:05:36.251 --> 00:05:39.025
the first instinct you have
is to sue me?!

93
00:05:39.697 --> 00:05:41.478
To sue the firm...?

94
00:05:42.123 --> 00:05:47.134
[Scoffs]
Well. I... I-i Don't even know...

95
00:05:48.853 --> 00:05:53.017
I- in what world is that anything
but the deepest betrayal

96
00:05:53.103 --> 00:05:55.947
of everything we worked so hard
to accomplish?

97
00:05:56.033 --> 00:05:57.344
In what world is that anything

98
00:05:57.392 --> 00:05:58.884
but the deepest betrayal
of our friendship?

99
00:05:58.931 --> 00:06:01.392
Howard. I could argue that
you're the one who betrayed me.

100
00:06:01.494 --> 00:06:02.978
That's bullshit.

101
00:06:03.470 --> 00:06:05.084
And you know it.

102
00:06:08.288 --> 00:06:09.988
This is pointless.

103
00:06:13.052 --> 00:06:14.189
Here.

104
00:06:14.525 --> 00:06:15.861
Just take this.

105
00:06:16.090 --> 00:06:17.890
[Paper rustles]

106
00:06:19.579 --> 00:06:21.079
$3 million?

107
00:06:21.236 --> 00:06:22.478
The first of three payments.

108
00:06:22.526 --> 00:06:24.204
as per
the partnership agreement.

109
00:06:24.619 --> 00:06:26.212
The firm can't afford this.

110
00:06:26.260 --> 00:06:27.478
Are you...

111
00:06:27.822 --> 00:06:29.652
You're not shutting down.
are you?

112
00:06:29.704 --> 00:06:32.040
I would never endanger the firm.

113
00:06:32.829 --> 00:06:35.228
This is mostly
from my personal funds.

114
00:06:35.689 --> 00:06:37.369
And a few loans.

115
00:06:41.212 --> 00:06:43.790
You're paying me
out of your own pocket.

116
00:06:48.383 --> 00:06:49.915
You won.

117
00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:03.120
(Hamlin:)
There's one last thing...

118
00:07:05.908 --> 00:07:07.619
[Indistinct conversations]

119
00:07:18.478 --> 00:07:20.178
[Sighs]

120
00:07:26.549 --> 00:07:27.987
(Hamlin:) Everybody!

121
00:07:28.095 --> 00:07:29.195
[Conversations stop]

122
00:07:29.330 --> 00:07:30.776
Thank you for gathering.

123
00:07:30.866 --> 00:07:33.396
I have some bittersweet news
to share.

124
00:07:33.523 --> 00:07:37.104
I'm sorry to say. but our
fearless leader. Charles McGill.

125
00:07:37.152 --> 00:07:38.782
will be leaving HHM.

126
00:07:38.849 --> 00:07:40.127
Effective immediately.

127
00:07:40.175 --> 00:07:42.604
I wanted to take this moment
to thank Chuck

128
00:07:42.730 --> 00:07:44.866
for everything he's Done
for HHM.

129
00:07:45.017 --> 00:07:47.014
We started off
with six employees.

130
00:07:47.181 --> 00:07:48.581
And Chuck helped grow us

131
00:07:48.629 --> 00:07:50.924
into one of the largest firms
in the state.

132
00:07:51.159 --> 00:07:55.095
We will be forever grateful
for his dedication.

133
00:07:57.651 --> 00:07:59.791
Do you have anything
you want to say?

134
00:08:03.792 --> 00:08:06.651
Alright. then.
Let's give him a hand!

135
00:08:06.934 --> 00:08:09.034
[Applause]

136
00:08:11.137 --> 00:08:13.137
[Indistinct talking]

137
00:08:48.675 --> 00:08:51.385
[Applause continues]

138
00:08:58.384 --> 00:09:00.524
[Birds chirping]

139
00:09:00.632 --> 00:09:03.447
[Vehicles passing]

140
00:09:07.908 --> 00:09:09.368
[Sighs]

141
00:09:12.351 --> 00:09:13.930
[Grunts softly]

142
00:09:18.815 --> 00:09:19.984
Hey.

143
00:09:20.443 --> 00:09:21.630
Morning.

144
00:09:21.678 --> 00:09:24.079
[Sighs]
Close.

145
00:09:29.243 --> 00:09:30.243
Gatorade.

146
00:09:30.704 --> 00:09:32.447
You need electrolytes.

147
00:09:35.054 --> 00:09:36.329
[Sighs]

148
00:09:38.645 --> 00:09:40.313
You hungry?

149
00:09:42.782 --> 00:09:45.087
I'll make you somethin'.

150
00:09:45.587 --> 00:09:48.540
Be right back.
Just finish that.

151
00:09:50.577 --> 00:09:53.107
[Footsteps depart]

152
00:09:53.405 --> 00:09:56.075
[Sizzling]

153
00:09:56.501 --> 00:09:57.780
(Kim:) Hey.

154
00:10:00.235 --> 00:10:02.009
I said I'd bring it to you.

155
00:10:02.196 --> 00:10:03.727
I needed to stretch my legs.

156
00:10:03.884 --> 00:10:06.221
[Sighs] Sit.
Eggs.

157
00:10:12.558 --> 00:10:14.352
This is. uh. twisted.

158
00:10:14.428 --> 00:10:15.907
Oh. thanks.

159
00:10:18.272 --> 00:10:22.735
This one-handed crap is gonna
get real old. real fast.

160
00:10:27.805 --> 00:10:29.219
Is there coffee?

161
00:10:29.376 --> 00:10:33.306
Sure.
But. uh. more gatorade first.

162
00:10:33.579 --> 00:10:35.447
[Pan thuds lightly]

163
00:10:39.134 --> 00:10:40.585
[Silverware clatters lightly]

164
00:10:40.712 --> 00:10:44.009
Alright. your. uh.
two options are...

165
00:10:44.253 --> 00:10:46.243
Good ole' ibuprofen

166
00:10:46.419 --> 00:10:48.391
which. uh. you know.
should take the edge off.

167
00:10:48.521 --> 00:10:51.189
Or the proverbial
"good stuff."

168
00:10:51.331 --> 00:10:52.761
[Pills rattle]

169
00:10:55.004 --> 00:10:57.404
The answer is always
"the good stuff."

170
00:10:57.759 --> 00:10:59.472
Right.
But food first.

171
00:10:59.735 --> 00:11:00.876
[Bottle thuds]

172
00:11:01.110 --> 00:11:03.111
[Clears throat]

173
00:11:20.159 --> 00:11:22.041
You're not feeding me. Jimmy.

174
00:11:22.526 --> 00:11:24.796
There are lines we do not cross.

175
00:11:29.478 --> 00:11:31.518
[Breathes deeply]

176
00:11:33.265 --> 00:11:35.525
I was looking into our lease
on the office.

177
00:11:35.630 --> 00:11:38.119
Um. we'd definitely take
a haircut if we broke it.

178
00:11:38.190 --> 00:11:40.050
But we are allowed to sublet.

179
00:11:40.164 --> 00:11:41.557
Might be our best option.

180
00:11:41.682 --> 00:11:43.791
Furniture's mostly rented
month to month.

181
00:11:43.955 --> 00:11:45.299
So that's not an issue.

182
00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:50.470
For you. I think you need
a desk. some file cabinets.

183
00:11:50.557 --> 00:11:52.260
A westlaw terminal...

184
00:11:52.493 --> 00:11:55.557
And. uh. haven't figured out
Francesca yet.

185
00:11:55.762 --> 00:11:58.518
That's another conversation.

186
00:11:59.253 --> 00:12:01.423
All that sound okay?

187
00:12:02.788 --> 00:12:05.252
Are you sure about this?

188
00:12:06.096 --> 00:12:08.839
I mean. even with
the sandpiper money...?

189
00:12:09.119 --> 00:12:12.401
Look.
After. uh...

190
00:12:13.893 --> 00:12:15.393
Everything...

191
00:12:15.924 --> 00:12:17.635
[Sighs]

192
00:12:18.400 --> 00:12:20.737
I Don't give a shit
about the office.

193
00:12:23.673 --> 00:12:25.393
[Breathes deeply]

194
00:12:28.487 --> 00:12:31.096
So can I start looking
for a tenant?

195
00:12:31.815 --> 00:12:33.471
Yeah.

196
00:12:33.781 --> 00:12:35.381
Yeah.

197
00:12:41.088 --> 00:12:42.707
[Fork clinking]

198
00:12:45.737 --> 00:12:48.580
I could've killed someone.
Jimmy.

199
00:12:49.216 --> 00:12:51.516
Yeah.<i> Yourself.</i>

200
00:12:53.615 --> 00:12:56.287
I worked most of last week
on maybe six hours of sleep.

201
00:12:56.335 --> 00:12:57.635
And then I...

202
00:13:00.010 --> 00:13:01.494
I crossed three lanes
of traffic.

203
00:13:01.542 --> 00:13:03.335
and I Don't remember
any of it...

204
00:13:03.471 --> 00:13:07.143
Look. you were just doing
what you thought you had to do.

205
00:13:07.409 --> 00:13:09.867
Because of me. You didn't
make me get in that car.

206
00:13:09.932 --> 00:13:11.562
That was all me.

207
00:13:13.401 --> 00:13:16.512
I'm an adult.
I made a choice.

208
00:13:24.296 --> 00:13:26.396
[Fork tapping]

209
00:13:31.635 --> 00:13:33.182
(Jimmy:) Hey.

210
00:13:33.393 --> 00:13:35.528
All I can say is.

211
00:13:35.846 --> 00:13:39.859
I am gonna fix things.

212
00:13:45.504 --> 00:13:47.814
[Fork tapping]

213
00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.900
[Car door creaks]

214
00:13:53.085 --> 00:13:54.947
[Vehicles passing]

215
00:13:55.147 --> 00:13:56.581
[Car door closes]

216
00:13:56.755 --> 00:13:58.408
[Car door creaks]

217
00:13:58.757 --> 00:14:00.861
[Whirring in distance]

218
00:14:01.026 --> 00:14:03.156
[Ringing in distance]

219
00:14:04.690 --> 00:14:07.166
[Dog barking in distance]

220
00:14:07.284 --> 00:14:08.784
[Car door closes]

221
00:14:12.037 --> 00:14:14.627
(Nacho:) Okay. So. we're gonna
do everything around back.

222
00:14:14.854 --> 00:14:18.690
It's mostly commercial around
here. so it's quiet at night.

223
00:14:18.924 --> 00:14:20.432
♪♪ <i>"Dinero sucio"</i> plays on radio...
We pull the trucks up to the doors.

224
00:14:20.479 --> 00:14:21.907
We unload right into the shop.

225
00:14:22.095 --> 00:14:23.580
[Sewing machine whirring]

226
00:14:23.696 --> 00:14:25.502
We can break down
the stuff in here.

227
00:14:25.698 --> 00:14:28.369
There's space in the back
for storing scales

228
00:14:28.529 --> 00:14:31.529
and. uh. supplies
when the shop's open.

229
00:14:31.938 --> 00:14:35.135
Should be able to process
everything overnight.

230
00:14:35.274 --> 00:14:37.267
I'd be here
to see it gets Done right...

231
00:14:37.455 --> 00:14:40.033
where's. uh. papi?

232
00:14:40.892 --> 00:14:42.517
I'll be taking care of all this.

233
00:14:42.685 --> 00:14:44.815
But he's good.

234
00:14:45.385 --> 00:14:46.838
Once we get everything packed.

235
00:14:46.886 --> 00:14:49.056
Arturo will pick up
and supervise distro.

236
00:14:49.188 --> 00:14:50.892
uh. make sure
everything is clear.

237
00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:53.197
Here's papi!

238
00:14:53.393 --> 00:14:54.860
Ah.

239
00:14:54.978 --> 00:14:56.391
♪♪

240
00:14:56.439 --> 00:14:58.119
[knocking. whirring]

241
00:14:58.264 --> 00:15:01.908
♪♪

242
00:15:01.955 --> 00:15:05.353
♪♪

243
00:15:05.779 --> 00:15:07.251
Don Hector...

244
00:15:07.407 --> 00:15:09.767
[Speaking spanish]

245
00:15:14.913 --> 00:15:16.478
[Chuckles]

246
00:15:17.289 --> 00:15:19.529
[Speaking spanish]

247
00:15:31.502 --> 00:15:32.931
Mm.

248
00:15:33.080 --> 00:15:35.150
[Money rustles]

249
00:15:45.156 --> 00:15:46.256
Mm?

250
00:15:50.057 --> 00:15:51.887
[Speaking spanish]

251
00:16:01.293 --> 00:16:02.510
[Sighs]

252
00:16:07.132 --> 00:16:08.832
(Nacho:) Papá...

253
00:16:39.831 --> 00:16:42.049
[Vehicles passing in distance]

254
00:16:42.393 --> 00:16:44.498
[Door closes. sound of
passing vehicles fades]

255
00:16:47.404 --> 00:16:48.840
[Door opens]

256
00:16:49.060 --> 00:16:50.971
[Vehicles passing in distance]

257
00:16:52.070 --> 00:16:53.370
[Door closes]

258
00:16:55.435 --> 00:16:57.983
He's old-fashioned.
He'll come around.

259
00:16:59.484 --> 00:17:01.554
[Dog barking in distance]

260
00:17:04.427 --> 00:17:06.052
Don Hector.

261
00:17:10.427 --> 00:17:11.912
I'll talk to him.

262
00:17:12.098 --> 00:17:14.058
He'll come around.

263
00:17:16.047 --> 00:17:18.232
I Don't trust him.

264
00:17:19.509 --> 00:17:21.239
[Door creaks]

265
00:17:27.012 --> 00:17:29.112
These are from Kevin and Paige.

266
00:17:29.196 --> 00:17:31.703
Well. I guess they're
from everybody at mesa verde.

267
00:17:31.784 --> 00:17:33.349
Oh! And there's a card.

268
00:17:33.452 --> 00:17:34.914
Somewhere in here.

269
00:17:35.008 --> 00:17:36.875
Ah. here!

270
00:17:37.656 --> 00:17:39.299
You brought the book?

271
00:17:39.374 --> 00:17:41.334
Um. sure.

272
00:17:45.696 --> 00:17:47.102
[Sighs]

273
00:17:47.233 --> 00:17:49.157
Mr. gatwood.

274
00:17:49.555 --> 00:17:50.782
The card wasn't clear.

275
00:17:50.882 --> 00:17:53.352
but I'm pretty sure
you're getting steaks. too.

276
00:17:53.696 --> 00:17:55.008
Really?

277
00:17:55.133 --> 00:17:57.242
Texas.
[Chuckles]

278
00:17:57.414 --> 00:17:59.227
He wishes you a speedy recovery.

279
00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:00.860
Mm-hmm.

280
00:18:03.448 --> 00:18:04.711
Okay.

281
00:18:04.859 --> 00:18:08.250
You are so lucky.

282
00:18:08.749 --> 00:18:11.875
I. um. I used to drive
that highway every weekend

283
00:18:11.937 --> 00:18:13.390
to visit my brother
and his kids.

284
00:18:13.516 --> 00:18:17.022
and I saw an accident
almost every single time.

285
00:18:17.145 --> 00:18:21.015
People die on that road
all the time.

286
00:18:25.468 --> 00:18:28.772
I-I already rescheduled
everything you had this week.

287
00:18:28.897 --> 00:18:31.475
But I didn't touch that meeting
with the regulator.

288
00:18:31.552 --> 00:18:34.413
I know that whole Utah timeline
is delicate. so...

289
00:18:34.576 --> 00:18:36.312
Right.
It's next Wednesday. right?

290
00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:38.577
Yes. And there's still a lot
of prep that we pushed

291
00:18:38.625 --> 00:18:40.646
so you could focus
on getting Mr. gatwood up

292
00:18:40.694 --> 00:18:42.016
by the end of the quarter.

293
00:18:42.147 --> 00:18:43.968
[Scoffs]
Which isn't happening now.

294
00:18:44.054 --> 00:18:46.179
Actually...?
I talked with Colleen.

295
00:18:46.262 --> 00:18:49.502
and she said everyone's fine
doing that meeting Monday.

296
00:18:49.574 --> 00:18:53.897
So. you know. that means
we could still slide in

297
00:18:54.055 --> 00:18:56.495
just under the deadline...

298
00:18:57.577 --> 00:18:59.207
[Scoffs]
Uh.

299
00:18:59.626 --> 00:19:00.684
Did you bring a breakdown

300
00:19:00.732 --> 00:19:02.235
of the documents I'll need
for next Wednesday?

301
00:19:02.282 --> 00:19:03.328
I would...
i would have to figure out...

302
00:19:03.375 --> 00:19:04.405
Yep.

303
00:19:04.453 --> 00:19:05.686
how long that'll take me.

304
00:19:05.828 --> 00:19:06.888
Right.

305
00:19:06.951 --> 00:19:09.054
[Papers rustling]

306
00:19:10.690 --> 00:19:13.382
That's four. six.

307
00:19:14.171 --> 00:19:15.585
Go to 11.

308
00:19:15.763 --> 00:19:17.944
[Papers rustling]

309
00:19:18.132 --> 00:19:21.882
♪♪

310
00:19:21.995 --> 00:19:25.827
♪♪

311
00:19:25.874 --> 00:19:28.991
♪♪

312
00:19:29.624 --> 00:19:31.374
found it.
Here you go.

313
00:19:31.545 --> 00:19:33.593
And Paige's timeline's
on the top.

314
00:19:33.775 --> 00:19:34.935
♪♪

315
00:19:35.074 --> 00:19:36.374
Kim?

316
00:19:37.218 --> 00:19:40.608
Y-You okay?
I-i can always come back...

317
00:19:41.321 --> 00:19:43.685
I'm gonna need you
to cancel gatwood

318
00:19:43.847 --> 00:19:45.253
and push everything else.

319
00:19:45.325 --> 00:19:46.591
What?
E-everything?

320
00:19:46.639 --> 00:19:48.106
Yeah.
Everything.

321
00:19:48.228 --> 00:19:49.802
[Book closes]
Uh. Okay.

322
00:19:49.909 --> 00:19:52.489
But first.
could you give me a ride?

323
00:19:53.067 --> 00:19:55.919
Absolutely.
Where to?

324
00:19:56.066 --> 00:19:57.685
[♪♪<i> Little l</i> plays in backgroun...]
Ms. Wexler sends her

325
00:19:57.732 --> 00:19:58.919
apologies. Mr. Gatwood.

326
00:19:59.065 --> 00:20:00.832
A-and she feels terrible
about this.

327
00:20:00.880 --> 00:20:02.810
but with her accident
and the recovery...

328
00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:06.749
she's just not gonna be able to
finish her work for you in time.

329
00:20:07.224 --> 00:20:08.950
Oh. of course. I'll tell her.

330
00:20:09.062 --> 00:20:10.802
A-and again.
she is very sorry.

331
00:20:10.850 --> 00:20:13.989
and I know she'll be giving you
a call herself soon.

332
00:20:14.435 --> 00:20:15.927
Well. yes.

333
00:20:16.098 --> 00:20:17.898
Ms. Wexler did ask me
to tell you

334
00:20:17.963 --> 00:20:20.233
she strongly recommends
schweikart and cokely.

335
00:20:20.281 --> 00:20:22.539
They're an exceptional firm.

336
00:20:22.696 --> 00:20:26.294
Okay. Well. I will send
that info over today.

337
00:20:26.567 --> 00:20:29.513
A-and Ms. w-Wexler
will follow up herself shortly.

338
00:20:29.603 --> 00:20:33.419
"Thanks for the meat." Uh. A-and
she says thank you for the steaks.

339
00:20:33.560 --> 00:20:35.255
She's so excited
to fire up that grill.

340
00:20:35.303 --> 00:20:36.600
[Chuckles]

341
00:20:36.743 --> 00:20:38.764
Thank you.
B-bye!

342
00:20:38.950 --> 00:20:40.724
Okay.
How many do I have?

343
00:20:41.169 --> 00:20:42.489
Nine...

344
00:20:42.850 --> 00:20:44.169
Good.

345
00:20:44.251 --> 00:20:48.083
♪♪

346
00:20:48.655 --> 00:20:51.115
[birds chirping.
dog barking in distance]

347
00:21:08.175 --> 00:21:09.490
[Engine starts]

348
00:21:09.538 --> 00:21:11.621
[Gearshift clicks]

349
00:21:12.295 --> 00:21:13.876
[Tires screech]

350
00:21:14.035 --> 00:21:15.711
[Engine shuts off]

351
00:21:16.068 --> 00:21:17.728
[Keys jingling]

352
00:21:26.136 --> 00:21:28.511
[Knock on door]
It's Jimmy.

353
00:21:29.363 --> 00:21:31.308
I know you Don't wanna see me.

354
00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:33.501
but. uh. I just want
to know you're okay.

355
00:21:36.777 --> 00:21:39.691
C'mon. Chuck.
I just want to see your face.

356
00:21:39.978 --> 00:21:41.716
C'mon. Chuck.
I just need a minute.

357
00:21:41.764 --> 00:21:43.690
I just need to know
you're alright.

358
00:21:43.774 --> 00:21:44.844
[Pounding on door]

359
00:21:44.915 --> 00:21:46.441
[Door opens]

360
00:21:46.511 --> 00:21:48.311
I'm alright. Jimmy.

361
00:21:48.415 --> 00:21:49.902
Oh. hey.
Good.

362
00:21:49.990 --> 00:21:52.183
I mean. I'm glad you're alright.

363
00:21:52.305 --> 00:21:53.371
I...

364
00:21:53.449 --> 00:21:55.191
Uh... Can I come in?

365
00:21:55.290 --> 00:21:57.190
Just talk for a minute...?

366
00:22:05.198 --> 00:22:07.722
♪♪ <i>"It never entered my mind"</i>
playing...

367
00:22:07.902 --> 00:22:11.800
♪♪

368
00:22:11.973 --> 00:22:15.715
♪♪

369
00:22:15.762 --> 00:22:19.385
♪♪

370
00:22:21.823 --> 00:22:24.260
[refrigerator humming softly]

371
00:22:24.384 --> 00:22:28.127
♪♪

372
00:22:28.174 --> 00:22:31.932
♪♪

373
00:22:32.143 --> 00:22:35.846
♪♪

374
00:22:35.893 --> 00:22:39.791
♪♪

375
00:22:40.893 --> 00:22:43.119
as you can see.
I'm more than alright.

376
00:22:43.553 --> 00:22:45.320
I'm very well. in fact.

377
00:22:45.564 --> 00:22:49.198
♪♪

378
00:22:49.393 --> 00:22:53.166
♪♪

379
00:22:56.450 --> 00:22:58.174
how...?

380
00:22:58.463 --> 00:23:00.190
I always told you
I'd get better.

381
00:23:00.243 --> 00:23:01.699
You just never believed me.

382
00:23:01.809 --> 00:23:03.309
♪♪

383
00:23:03.455 --> 00:23:05.190
sure I did.

384
00:23:05.392 --> 00:23:06.759
♪♪

385
00:23:07.010 --> 00:23:11.463
but. Chuck
[Chuckling] This is great!

386
00:23:11.665 --> 00:23:13.674
♪♪

387
00:23:13.791 --> 00:23:15.518
how did you do it?

388
00:23:15.596 --> 00:23:17.088
What was it you wanted?

389
00:23:17.197 --> 00:23:19.064
Beyond "proof of life"?

390
00:23:19.167 --> 00:23:20.634
♪♪

391
00:23:20.807 --> 00:23:23.010
Oh. [Sighs]

392
00:23:24.376 --> 00:23:27.645
[Sighs]
S-something happened.

393
00:23:27.834 --> 00:23:30.402
and it made me
think about what ha...

394
00:23:30.612 --> 00:23:32.471
went down between you and me.

395
00:23:32.519 --> 00:23:34.815
And...[Sighs]

396
00:23:35.080 --> 00:23:37.807
I wanted to say. in hindsight.

397
00:23:38.229 --> 00:23:40.299
I could've
made different choices.

398
00:23:40.427 --> 00:23:42.330
Is that so?
Yeah.

399
00:23:42.460 --> 00:23:44.854
I mean. I'm not saying
it's all on me.

400
00:23:44.910 --> 00:23:46.455
It's not.

401
00:23:46.807 --> 00:23:49.119
But if I had to do it
all over again

402
00:23:49.636 --> 00:23:54.080
[clicks tongue] I would maybe
do some things differently.

403
00:23:54.690 --> 00:23:57.112
And I just thought
you should know that.

404
00:23:57.877 --> 00:23:59.854
That you have regrets?

405
00:24:00.263 --> 00:24:02.682
Yeah.
I have regrets.

406
00:24:02.979 --> 00:24:05.676
- Mm.
- [Sighs]

407
00:24:05.846 --> 00:24:07.486
Why?

408
00:24:10.589 --> 00:24:12.877
[Chuckling]
'Cause you're my brother.

409
00:24:13.604 --> 00:24:16.604
There aren't that many
of us McGills left.

410
00:24:16.688 --> 00:24:19.455
and. uh. I think we should
stick together.

411
00:24:19.531 --> 00:24:22.080
No.
Why have regrets at all?

412
00:24:22.128 --> 00:24:24.315
What's the point?

413
00:24:25.080 --> 00:24:26.353
What do you mean?

414
00:24:26.449 --> 00:24:29.309
Well. look at you.
You're in so much pain.

415
00:24:29.476 --> 00:24:32.323
Why are you putting yourself
through all this?

416
00:24:32.573 --> 00:24:34.182
'Cause I wanted to tell you...

417
00:24:34.230 --> 00:24:35.377
that you have regrets.

418
00:24:35.479 --> 00:24:37.577
And I'm telling you:
Don't bother.

419
00:24:37.751 --> 00:24:39.940
What's the point?

420
00:24:40.432 --> 00:24:42.202
You're just gonna
keep hurting people.

421
00:24:42.274 --> 00:24:44.971
That's not true.
Jimmy. this is what you do.

422
00:24:45.089 --> 00:24:48.627
You hurt people.
Over and over and over.

423
00:24:48.698 --> 00:24:50.916
And then there's this show
of remorse...

424
00:24:50.976 --> 00:24:52.076
it's not a "show"!

425
00:24:52.179 --> 00:24:53.580
I know you Don't think
it's a show.

426
00:24:53.629 --> 00:24:55.791
I Don't doubt your emotions
are real.

427
00:24:56.010 --> 00:24:58.283
but what's the point
of all the sad faces

428
00:24:58.331 --> 00:24:59.885
and the gnashing of teeth?

429
00:25:00.025 --> 00:25:02.205
If you're not going to
change your behavior...

430
00:25:02.253 --> 00:25:03.526
[chuckling] And you won't...

431
00:25:03.574 --> 00:25:07.346
I can change... Why not just
skip the whole exercise?

432
00:25:07.614 --> 00:25:11.596
In the end. you're going to
hurt everyone around you.

433
00:25:11.916 --> 00:25:13.049
You can't help it.

434
00:25:13.213 --> 00:25:15.674
So. stop apologizing
and accept it.

435
00:25:15.757 --> 00:25:17.391
Embrace it.

436
00:25:17.478 --> 00:25:20.354
Frankly. I'd have more respect
for you if you did.

437
00:25:20.694 --> 00:25:23.065
What about you. Chuck?
Hmm?

438
00:25:23.293 --> 00:25:25.453
You didn't do anything wrong?

439
00:25:25.955 --> 00:25:27.619
You're just an innocent victim?

440
00:25:27.697 --> 00:25:30.632
Let me put your mind at ease.
Jimmy.

441
00:25:30.837 --> 00:25:33.135
You Don't have to
make up with me.

442
00:25:33.422 --> 00:25:36.518
We Don't have to
understand each other.

443
00:25:36.908 --> 00:25:39.604
Things are fine
the way they are.

444
00:25:40.174 --> 00:25:41.596
[Sighs]

445
00:25:41.948 --> 00:25:43.049
[Chuckling] Hey.

446
00:25:43.135 --> 00:25:45.497
[Sighs]

447
00:25:46.920 --> 00:25:48.998
I Don't want to hurt
your feelings...

448
00:25:50.612 --> 00:25:54.615
But the truth is you've never
mattered all that much to me.

449
00:25:54.995 --> 00:25:57.195
[Clock ticking]

450
00:26:07.072 --> 00:26:10.012
[Light thudding]

451
00:26:11.935 --> 00:26:13.622
[Sighs]

452
00:26:36.503 --> 00:26:38.598
[Clears throat]

453
00:26:49.466 --> 00:26:53.488
[Door opens. closes]

454
00:26:55.385 --> 00:26:57.205
[Sighing]

455
00:27:10.702 --> 00:27:11.904
[Light switch clicks]

456
00:27:16.041 --> 00:27:17.568
[Pills rattle]

457
00:27:18.011 --> 00:27:19.941
[Sighing]

458
00:27:25.736 --> 00:27:27.306
Gold comforter.

459
00:27:27.900 --> 00:27:29.360
Green chair.

460
00:27:29.906 --> 00:27:31.406
Brown journal.

461
00:27:31.752 --> 00:27:33.628
[Slurps]

462
00:27:36.295 --> 00:27:37.888
[Sighs]

463
00:27:38.265 --> 00:27:39.724
Hm.

464
00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:43.380
[Breathing deeply]

465
00:27:46.353 --> 00:27:47.553
Hm.

466
00:28:06.826 --> 00:28:08.521
[light switch clicks]
[Sighs]

467
00:28:08.628 --> 00:28:12.451
♪♪

468
00:28:12.538 --> 00:28:16.310
♪♪

469
00:28:16.357 --> 00:28:19.826
♪♪

470
00:28:19.873 --> 00:28:22.935
♪♪

471
00:28:23.343 --> 00:28:25.310
[door opens]

472
00:28:25.791 --> 00:28:29.123
[Switches clicking]

473
00:28:29.176 --> 00:28:30.451
Ah.

474
00:28:30.629 --> 00:28:32.296
♪♪

475
00:28:32.404 --> 00:28:34.652
[switches clicking]

476
00:28:34.810 --> 00:28:38.584
♪♪

477
00:28:38.826 --> 00:28:42.677
♪♪

478
00:28:42.724 --> 00:28:46.388
♪♪

479
00:28:46.489 --> 00:28:50.138
♪♪

480
00:28:50.185 --> 00:28:53.904
♪♪

481
00:28:58.958 --> 00:29:01.534
[knocker taps]

482
00:29:02.833 --> 00:29:05.401
Jimmy.
What a nice surprise.

483
00:29:05.519 --> 00:29:08.019
Irene!
As beautiful as ever!

484
00:29:08.139 --> 00:29:10.409
Why Don't you come in?

485
00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:12.627
Can I get you some tea?
[Door closes]

486
00:29:12.744 --> 00:29:14.276
Oh. I Don't want to be a bother.

487
00:29:14.403 --> 00:29:16.499
I just have a couple things
to drop off.

488
00:29:16.604 --> 00:29:18.932
Well.
w-what is all this?

489
00:29:18.980 --> 00:29:22.284
Well. when we win. we celebrate.

490
00:29:23.113 --> 00:29:24.943
That's very sweet.

491
00:29:25.027 --> 00:29:27.377
Yes. And I didn't forget
about Oscar and Felix.

492
00:29:27.425 --> 00:29:29.471
I've got some kitty toys
and catnip in there

493
00:29:29.527 --> 00:29:30.879
for those two little rascals.

494
00:29:30.927 --> 00:29:33.283
Oh.
You shouldn't have. Jimmy.

495
00:29:33.393 --> 00:29:35.323
Of course I should.
[Claps hands]

496
00:29:35.565 --> 00:29:37.323
Now. have you given any thought

497
00:29:37.371 --> 00:29:40.041
to how you want to spend
that settlement money?

498
00:29:42.096 --> 00:29:43.456
I Don't know...

499
00:29:43.536 --> 00:29:45.307
Well. I'll tell you what I'd do.

500
00:29:45.534 --> 00:29:47.276
Alaskan cruise.

501
00:29:47.473 --> 00:29:51.803
You can walk on a glacier
under the Aurora borealis.

502
00:29:55.237 --> 00:29:59.885
And if Alaska's too cold.
maybe a European river cruise.

503
00:30:00.010 --> 00:30:01.385
Float on down the Danube.

504
00:30:01.493 --> 00:30:04.135
I bet you and the ladies
could split a deluxe suite.

505
00:30:04.278 --> 00:30:06.377
Get into all sorts of trouble.

506
00:30:06.531 --> 00:30:08.002
That sounds very nice.

507
00:30:08.050 --> 00:30:11.573
but... I Don't think
they'd really want to.

508
00:30:11.940 --> 00:30:13.901
Why not?

509
00:30:14.631 --> 00:30:18.315
They're still... Upset.

510
00:30:19.311 --> 00:30:23.021
They<i> must</i> be excited about
the settlement though. right?

511
00:30:25.142 --> 00:30:27.604
(Jimmy:) But you can't let
one little misunderstanding

512
00:30:27.652 --> 00:30:30.166
destroy years of friendship.
<i>["Steal away"</i> plays in background]

513
00:30:30.491 --> 00:30:33.091
(Myrtle:) Oh. it's just not
the same. Jimmy.

514
00:30:33.156 --> 00:30:34.756
She showed her true colors.

515
00:30:34.804 --> 00:30:36.541
When it came to that settlement.

516
00:30:36.637 --> 00:30:39.175
we were the furthest things
from her mind.

517
00:30:39.333 --> 00:30:40.432
It just took her a bit

518
00:30:40.513 --> 00:30:42.909
to realize what was important
to you.

519
00:30:43.370 --> 00:30:45.237
She came around.

520
00:30:45.470 --> 00:30:47.065
She just wanted

521
00:30:47.113 --> 00:30:49.635
to get back on our good side...

522
00:30:50.342 --> 00:30:52.955
Okay.
How do you trust someone

523
00:30:53.131 --> 00:30:56.400
who bends any way
the wind is blowing?

524
00:30:56.538 --> 00:30:58.502
Where is her integrity?

525
00:30:58.716 --> 00:31:02.441
♪♪

526
00:31:04.453 --> 00:31:06.980
well. I can't help
but blame myself.

527
00:31:07.085 --> 00:31:08.636
You were just trying to help.

528
00:31:08.699 --> 00:31:11.394
No. I stuck my nose in
where it didn't belong.

529
00:31:11.495 --> 00:31:13.917
and I... stirred the pot.

530
00:31:14.265 --> 00:31:15.347
So...

531
00:31:15.833 --> 00:31:17.214
[Scoffs]

532
00:31:17.368 --> 00:31:19.722
Look. if you want
to blame someone.

533
00:31:20.224 --> 00:31:22.159
you should blame me.

534
00:31:22.340 --> 00:31:23.745
♪♪

535
00:31:23.810 --> 00:31:25.894
